orary Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Boyaca]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Liberator]]\n[[Category:People from Elizabeth, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:United States Navy World War II admirals]]\n[[Category:Pingry School alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:United States naval attach\u00e9s]]\n", "name_user": "QueenofBattle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Halsey_Jr."}
{"title_page": "Nicholas Marr", "text_new": "[[File:Marr.jpg|thumb|Nicholas Marr, circa 1930s]]\n\n'''Nicholas Yakovlevich Marr''' ({{lang-ru|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0439 \u042f\u0301\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0440}}, ''Nikolay Yakovlevich Marr''; {{lang-ka|\u10dc\u10d8\u10d9\u10dd\u10da\u10dd\u10d6 \u10d8\u10d0\u10d9\u10dd\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10eb\u10d4 \u10db\u10d0\u10e0\u10d8}}, ''Nikoloz Iak'obis dze Mari''; {{OldStyleDateDY|6 January|1865|25 December 1864}} &ndash; 20 December 1934) was a [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]-born [[historian]] and [[Linguistics|linguist]] who gained a reputation as a scholar of the [[Caucasus]] during the 1910s before embarking on his [[Japhetic theory (linguistics)|\"Japhetic theory\"]] on the [[origin of language]] (from 1924), now considered as pseudo-scientific,<ref>See e.g. [http://russcience.chat.ru/papers/alp93sp.htm#_ftnref1 \u0412.\u041c.\u0410\u043b\u043f\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \"\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0440, \u043c\u0430\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043c \u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0437\u043c\"]</ref> and related speculative linguistic hypotheses.\n\nMarr's hypotheses were used as a rationale in the campaign during the 1920\u201330s in the [[Soviet Union]] of introduction of [[Latin alphabet]]s for smaller ethnicities of the country. In 1950, the \"Japhetic theory\" fell from official favour, with [[Joseph Stalin]] denouncing it as anti-Marxist.\n\n==Biography==\n[[Image:Marr mother 1870.jpg|frame|Marr with mother, 1870]]\nMarr was born in [[Kutaisi]], Georgia (then part of the [[Russian Empire]]), in the family of the [[Scot]] James Murray (phonetically adapted: Marr) (aged 71<ref name=\"Rayfield\">{{cite web|url=http://britishgeorgiansociety.org/events/11-past/206-nokolai-marr-a-talk-by-donald-rayfield-17-february|title=Nikolai Marr - a talk by Donald Rayfield 17 February|publisher=British Georgian Society|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>) who founded the [[botanical garden]] of the city, and a young [[Georgians|Georgian]] woman (Agrafina Magularia). His parents spoke different languages, and neither of them understood [[Russian language|Russian]]. Having graduated from the [[St Petersburg University]], he taught there beginning in 1891, becoming dean of the [[Oriental]] faculty in 1911 and member of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences]] in 1912. Between 1904 and 1917 he undertook yearly excavations at the ancient [[Armenia]]n capital of [[Ani (Armenia)|Ani]].<ref name=\"marr\">{{cite book\n  | last =Marr\n  | first =Nicolas\n  | title =Ani - R\u00eave d'Arm\u00e9nie\n  | publisher =Anagramme Editions\n  | year =2001\n  | isbn =978-2-914571-00-5}}</ref>\n\nHe died in [[Leningrad]].\n\n==Japhetic theory==\n{{Main|Japhetic theory}}\nMarr gained some recognition with his Japhetic theory, postulating the common origin of [[Caucasian languages|Caucasian]], [[Afro-Asiatic|Semitic-Hamitic]], and [[Basque language|Basque]] languages. In 1924, he went even further and proclaimed that all the languages of the world descended from a single [[proto-language]] which had consisted of four \"diffused exclamations\": ''sal, ber, yon, rosh''. Although the languages undergo certain stages of development, his method of ''linguistic paleontology'' claims to make it possible to discern elements of primordial exclamations in any given language. One of his followers was [[Valerian Borisovich Aptekar]], and one of his opponents was [[Arnold Chikobava]].\n\n==Bibliography==\nSelected publications:\n*{{cite book |title=Collections of proverbs Vartan: Izsl\u0463dovan\u0456e \n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr, Vardan (Aygektsi)\n |publisher=Type. Imp. akademii Sciences |year=1899}}\n*{{cite book |title=Chanskago Grammar\n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr\n |publisher=Type. imp. Akadem\u0456i Sciences |year=1910 |pages=240}}\n*{{cite book |title=Amran \n |author=Jah Gato , Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr\n |publisher=The Academy |year=1932 |pages=162}}\n*{{cite book |title=Tristan and Isolda: love of the heroine of feudal Europe to the matriarchal goddess Afrevrazii \n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr\n |publisher=Publishing House of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR |year=1932\n |pages=286}}\n*{{cite book |title=Language and Society \n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr, [[Valerian Borisovich Aptekar]]\n |publisher=State Academy of the History of Material Culture |year=1934}}\n*{{cite book |title=Collected articles\n |authors=Nikolay Yakovlevich Marr, [[Valerian Borisovich Aptekar]]\n |publisher=Power to the Soviets |year=1936\n |pages=207}}\n*{{cite book |title=Description of the Georgian manuscripts of Sinai Monastery\n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr\n |publisher=Publishing House of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR |year=1940\n |pages=276}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Nicholas Yacolevich Marr 2001. ''Ani'' (with forewords by Jean-Pierre Kibarian and Parouyr Mouradi), Anagramme Ed.(Paris), (reprint).\n* [[Ekaterina Velmezova]] 2007. ''Les lois du sens: la s\u00e9mantique marriste''. Bern: Peter Lang, 2007 \u2014 (Slavica Helvetica 77) \u2014 {{ISBN|978-3-03911-208-1}}.\n* [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia|\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f]] / [https://dlib.rsl.ru/viewer/01008005507#?page=155 \u0433\u043b. \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u041e. \u042e. \u0428\u043c\u0438\u0434\u0442. - \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 : \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f, 1926-. - 26 \u0441\u043c. \u0422. 38: \u041c\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044f\u0440\u0438\u044f - \u041c\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438. - 1938. - (416) \u0441., (19) \u043b. \u0438\u043b., \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0440., \u0444\u0430\u043a\u0441. : \u0438\u043b., \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u044b, \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0440., \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b./ \u0421. 261-264]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/stalin/works/1950/jun/20.htm Marxism and Problems of Linguistics, by Joseph Stalin]\n*[http://www.virtualani.org/marr/index.htm Nikoli Marr and his excavations at Ani]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000341/http://slovo.iphil.ru/virtlab/50/marr/piatitomnik/ Nikolai Marr's Writings 5 Vols, Djvu]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marr}}\n[[Category:1864 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kutaisi]]\n[[Category:People from Kutais Governorate]]\n[[Category:Georgian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:20th-century linguists]]\n[[Category:Paleolinguists]]\n[[Category:Linguists from Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Historians from Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the St Petersburg Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences (1917\u201325)]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the USSR Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Armenian studies scholars]]\n[[Category:Linguists of Caucasian languages]]\n[[Category:Linguists of Kartvelian languages]]\n[[Category:Burials at Kazachye Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Marr.jpg|thumb|Nicholas Marr, circa 1930s]]\n\n'''Nicholas Yakovlevich Marr''' ({{lang-ru|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0439 \u042f\u0301\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0440}}, ''Nikolay Yakovlevich Marr''; {{lang-ka|\u10dc\u10d8\u10d9\u10dd\u10da\u10dd\u10d6 \u10d8\u10d0\u10d9\u10dd\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10eb\u10d4 \u10db\u10d0\u10e0\u10d8}}, ''Nikoloz Iak'obis dze Mari''; {{OldStyleDateDY|6 January|1865|25 December 1864}} &ndash; 20 December 1934) was a [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]-born [[historian]] and linguist who gained a reputation as a scholar of the [[Caucasus]] during the 1910s before embarking on his [[Japhetic theory (linguistics)|\"Japhetic theory\"]] on the [[origin of language]] (from 1924), now considered as pseudo-scientific,<ref>See e.g. [http://russcience.chat.ru/papers/alp93sp.htm#_ftnref1 \u0412.\u041c.\u0410\u043b\u043f\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \"\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0440, \u043c\u0430\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043c \u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0437\u043c\"]</ref> and related speculative linguistic hypotheses.\n\nMarr's hypotheses were used as a rationale in the campaign during the 1920\u201330s in the [[Soviet Union]] of introduction of [[Latin alphabet]]s for smaller ethnicities of the country. In 1950, the \"Japhetic theory\" fell from official favour, with [[Joseph Stalin]] denouncing it as anti-Marxist.\n\n==Biography==\n[[Image:Marr mother 1870.jpg|frame|Marr with mother, 1870]]\nMarr was born in [[Kutaisi]], Georgia (then part of the [[Russian Empire]]), in the family of the [[Scot]] James Murray (phonetically adapted: Marr) (aged 71<ref name=\"Rayfield\">{{cite web|url=http://britishgeorgiansociety.org/events/11-past/206-nokolai-marr-a-talk-by-donald-rayfield-17-february|title=Nikolai Marr - a talk by Donald Rayfield 17 February|publisher=British Georgian Society|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>) who founded the [[botanical garden]] of the city, and a young [[Georgians|Georgian]] woman (Agrafina Magularia). His parents spoke different languages, and neither of them understood [[Russian language|Russian]]. Having graduated from the [[St Petersburg University]], he taught there beginning in 1891, becoming dean of the [[Oriental]] faculty in 1911 and member of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences]] in 1912. Between 1904 and 1917 he undertook yearly excavations at the ancient [[Armenia]]n capital of [[Ani (Armenia)|Ani]].<ref name=\"marr\">{{cite book\n  | last =Marr\n  | first =Nicolas\n  | title =Ani - R\u00eave d'Arm\u00e9nie\n  | publisher =Anagramme Editions\n  | year =2001\n  | isbn =978-2-914571-00-5}}</ref>\n\nHe died in [[Leningrad]].\n\n==Japhetic theory==\n{{Main|Japhetic theory}}\nMarr gained some recognition with his Japhetic theory, postulating the common origin of [[Caucasian languages|Caucasian]], [[Afro-Asiatic|Semitic-Hamitic]], and [[Basque language|Basque]] languages. In 1924, he went even further and proclaimed that all the languages of the world descended from a single [[proto-language]] which had consisted of four \"diffused exclamations\": ''sal, ber, yon, rosh''. Although the languages undergo certain stages of development, his method of ''linguistic paleontology'' claims to make it possible to discern elements of primordial exclamations in any given language. One of his followers was [[Valerian Borisovich Aptekar]], and one of his opponents was [[Arnold Chikobava]].\n\n==Bibliography==\nSelected publications:\n*{{cite book |title=Collections of proverbs Vartan: Izsl\u0463dovan\u0456e \n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr, Vardan (Aygektsi)\n |publisher=Type. Imp. akademii Sciences |year=1899}}\n*{{cite book |title=Chanskago Grammar\n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr\n |publisher=Type. imp. Akadem\u0456i Sciences |year=1910 |pages=240}}\n*{{cite book |title=Amran \n |author=Jah Gato , Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr\n |publisher=The Academy |year=1932 |pages=162}}\n*{{cite book |title=Tristan and Isolda: love of the heroine of feudal Europe to the matriarchal goddess Afrevrazii \n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr\n |publisher=Publishing House of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR |year=1932\n |pages=286}}\n*{{cite book |title=Language and Society \n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr, [[Valerian Borisovich Aptekar]]\n |publisher=State Academy of the History of Material Culture |year=1934}}\n*{{cite book |title=Collected articles\n |authors=Nikolay Yakovlevich Marr, [[Valerian Borisovich Aptekar]]\n |publisher=Power to the Soviets |year=1936\n |pages=207}}\n*{{cite book |title=Description of the Georgian manuscripts of Sinai Monastery\n |author=Nikolai Yakovlevich Marr\n |publisher=Publishing House of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR |year=1940\n |pages=276}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Nicholas Yacolevich Marr 2001. ''Ani'' (with forewords by Jean-Pierre Kibarian and Parouyr Mouradi), Anagramme Ed.(Paris), (reprint).\n* [[Ekaterina Velmezova]] 2007. ''Les lois du sens: la s\u00e9mantique marriste''. Bern: Peter Lang, 2007 \u2014 (Slavica Helvetica 77) \u2014 {{ISBN|978-3-03911-208-1}}.\n* [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia|\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f]] / [https://dlib.rsl.ru/viewer/01008005507#?page=155 \u0433\u043b. \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u041e. \u042e. \u0428\u043c\u0438\u0434\u0442. - \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 : \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f, 1926-. - 26 \u0441\u043c. \u0422. 38: \u041c\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044f\u0440\u0438\u044f - \u041c\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438. - 1938. - (416) \u0441., (19) \u043b. \u0438\u043b., \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0440., \u0444\u0430\u043a\u0441. : \u0438\u043b., \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u044b, \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0440., \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b./ \u0421. 261-264]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/stalin/works/1950/jun/20.htm Marxism and Problems of Linguistics, by Joseph Stalin]\n*[http://www.virtualani.org/marr/index.htm Nikoli Marr and his excavations at Ani]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000341/http://slovo.iphil.ru/virtlab/50/marr/piatitomnik/ Nikolai Marr's Writings 5 Vols, Djvu]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{